God is so kind. 

For years… well, decades, I have prayed for one thing.  A person that would be a Godly, consistent, loyal and patient best friend that would walk with me through life.  A man that would both support me and challenge me (and not be afraid to say no - I can be quite stubborn and persistent).

God provides. 

A little over a year ago, I was moving into a storage unit and headed to Nashville.  I was overwhelmed, seeking the Lord and at a bit of a crossroads. 

Little did I know, the man that I met late that night would show up for me in ways that only the Lord could have orchestrated. 

God is so faithful. 

Kyle Kuykendall has completely changed my life. He has softened my heart in ways I couldn’t imagine, he has been the consistent best friend I prayed for and he has been more persistent in faith, in life and in our love story than any person I’ve ever met. 

God is love. 

On December 9, this man asked me to marry him in the same storage unit we met 497 days prior…and I said yes!

God is good. 

Psalm 34 refers to a heart longing for the Lord to hear and respond. 

The Lord heard my prayers and sat with me for years as my heart waited and longed.  While it took way longer than I anticipated, my prayers were answered.  Our love story is molded and shaped by our past and the Lord’s timing is truly perfect.  It’s been so sweet to witness the Lord’s perfect attention to detail that unraveled and bound our hearts together.

The Lord is faithful and I am forever thankful for this man that has captured my heart and loves me unconditionally. 
 
I can’t wait to continue this journey and see what God will do next!  Mr. Kuykendall, see you on March 18, 2023.

(Yup! 90 days from today!)

The story of Jesus’ birth is a story marked by the advent season of waiting, peace, love, joy and hope.  But it is a story marked by unexpected hospitality.  The innkeeper didn’t have room in his inn, but he offered them all he had.  He was willing to extend hospitality and generously give all he had.  And in the midst of offering a stable, he offered a place for the Savior of the World to rest that first night. 

He didn’t have the perfect meal created or the nicest bedroom available.  He didn’t clean the baseboards or vacuum the carpets.  What he did have was a willing heart and an open door. 

Isn’t that the heart of Jesus?  He calls us to be willing to love others and invite them in.  This Christmas Season, I pray we don’t get too busy for the season and we learn from the Innkeeper.  We use this as a a time to reflect on how well we love others and how well we invite them in.  Take time to love and open yourself to the beauty and blessing of hospitality.

Merry Christmas from our sweet little future family to yours! ❤️🎄❤️

I’ve been in my own world lately… and I’m so happy about it! Two weeks ago my sweet sisters planned a bachelorette party for me and some of my friends and it was amazing!! Like literally the best party I could have ever dreamed of having!! ❤️❤️ shout out to @mollyannesandefur and @lauraleighturner for the time and thought that went into it!! The best!!

We laughed and cried and danced and played laser tag and it was perfect! Every detail thought about and curated just for me in celebration of our wedding! 

What I think is even cooler is that we stopped by the chapel that Kyle and I will get married in over the weekend and we got to be in a place that 42 days later I would be getting married in.  What is even better is that the day I came home I entered the last 40 days of my singleness. 

I couldn’t help but be so thankful for the women that prayed over me and helped celebrate what was to come but ushered me into the final stretch of a time period of my life I never thought would end.  I seriously have the best friends - I am so blessed!! 

Singleness has been a journey, and I guess it’s ironic I post about it on Valentine’s Day, but as I close this chapter I’m so thankful for it.  This day always stung a bit for me because I never had “a man” to share it with (amazing what Hallmark will do to an impressionable mind) but now that I have someone I find my heart aching for those that find themselves in that stage. In fact, tonight, I gathered with women in my home, with Jesus. Friends - don’t get so caught up in life that you forget your community!

I’ve learned a lot over the last 15 years in singleness but the biggest one was from God.  I heard Him almost audibly tell me “I need to cultivate characteristics that draw people to Him, not men to me.” 

Community is so important and I will forever be thankful for this time (this very long time) that I spent in singleness learning to rely on God and learning how to bring people together and gather around the table. 

So thankful for friends that are generous with their time and their energy to come and celebrate me in Branson.  Cyndi Lauper was right… girls just wanna have #smore fun!

Now… let’s get married! 42 hours!!! 🥰🥰🥰

It’s a solemn day.  A day when Jesus are His last meal with his best friends and also the day he was betrayed by one of them.  Sitting in Barcelona and hearing the bells from all of the churches around at sundown, to remind us of His betrayal… is sobering. 

This might be my favorite passage in the entire Bible. Why? Because in one sentence Jesus shows us our importance to Him.  Not only did He know He would be betrayed and what the next few days held for Him… but in the midst of that, He eagerly wanted to eat with His friends around a table. 

What if Jesus was sitting at your table right now. Imagine that. Close your eyes if you need to and imagine it... Jesus, the God of the universe is sitting there and in His calm and tenor tone of voice he intentionally utters the words... I have eagerly waited to eat this meal with you.

Let’s think about the context of this passage because that is super important to understanding what God is trying to say to us.

The Feast of the Unleavened Bread was happening during Passover. This Passover meal, the yearly commemoration of God’s redemptive work on behalf of His people.

And now, this meal, one in which Jews and Israelites for centuries had been used to remind themselves of God’s faithfulness to fulfill His covenant to deliver His people from slavery…. was sitting amongst them fulfilling the promise. 

Jesus wants to sit with you at the Table! He eagerly waits for you to pull up a seat and join Him!

In today’s TableTalk over on my blog (link in bio), I am talking about Halloween and ways that, as Christians, we don’t have to avoid this holiday, but we can embrace it and use it as an opportunity to show Christ’s love through hospitality. 

As Halloween rolls around, many of us start thinking about pumpkins, costumes, and candy. Halloween, or All Hallowed's Eve, is often associated with spooky decor and haunted tales, but as Christians, we have the opportunity to bring light and love into this season through hospitality. 

Halloween doesn’t have to be avoided.  It doesn't have to be a time of fear and darkness. But, by focusing on hospitality, kindness, and love, we can transform this day into an opportunity to share the light of Christ with our community. 

Be intentional about bringing Jesus into Halloween and being a beacon of hope in a world that sometimes feels scary.

As you embrace the beauty of this fall season with the cooler temps and earlier sunsets, remember to indulge in the simple pleasures that it offers. 

Whip up this Apple Crisp, top it with Homemade Vanilla Ice Cream, and let the cinnamon-infused aroma and cozy flavors of fall fill your home and heart.

When I started 2023 praying that my year would be a year focused on the word EMBRACE…. I’m not sure I knew what God had in store for me. 

I just knew I wanted to live the year in a way that embraces each moment in a perfectly present way. I wanted to feel joy rise from within, because to me “embrace” was pairing contentment with delight.

Embrace means deep connection and pressing in.  I wanted to press in this year to what God had in store for me, not missing a moment. I wanted to connect deeply with the people and things that matter to me. And boy did I embrace this year. And God showed up and embraced me back. 

I can’t look back on this year and forget that the biggest embrace I’ve experienced happened this year. The embrace of marriage. Kyle has made my 2023 a year I’ll always remember and cherish.  From creating our own traditions (and family), to chasing adventures and feeling the unconditional love from your best friend and husband… this year will be the one to beat.

I can’t wait for 2024. My word: PACE.  We will be in our new house as a family and will be creating new rhythms while finding different paces for different moments of life.  slow. steady. sprint. 

But in all moments and rhythms “let us run with endurance the race God has set before us. We do this by keeping our eyes on Jesus …” Hebrews 12:1b-2a. 

Happy 2024!
